Here's a typical setup:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Services
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reuse one instance to avoid socket exhaustion. Thread-safe by design. |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient`, holds no per-user state — one instance is enough and keeps an in-memory cache consistent. |
| `MainViewModel` | **Transient** | Each navigation creates fresh state (loaded items, selections). Avoids stale data when returning to a page. |
| `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Same — each detail screen needs its own instance bound to a specific item. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Match their ViewModels. A new page instance gets a new ViewModel via constructor injection. |

**When you'd use `AddScoped`:** MAUI doesn't have a built-in scope-per-page, so `Scoped` behaves like `Singleton`. It's generally not useful here — stick with Singleton + Transient.

**Key rule of thumb:** services that are stateless or hold shared state → **Singleton**. Anything tied to a screen or user interaction → **Transient**.
